    9:40 AM - 11:00 AM | Accounting

    Faculty: Ron Kasznik

    Financial Statements

    Accounting is the measurement of economic activity in value terms for decision-making. Company financial statements are a key product of the measurement process and a major component of the financial reporting activities of the firm. In this session, we will discuss the role of the primary financial statements (balance sheet, income statement, and statement of cash flows), and identify some of the key relations among them. We also demonstrate the mapping between underlying economic events and financial statements, and how this mapping may affect inferences about future profitability and cash flows.

    Pre-session preparation:

    • Videos: Introduction to Financial Statements (there are 7 short videos)

     Preparation Question(s):

    • None

    Kasznik - Videos: Introduction to Financial Statements
    You are expected to watch all 7 videos prior to the start of the session.


    11:00 AM - 11:20 AM | BREAK (faculty discretion; times are approximate)


    11:20 AM - 12:40 PM | Accounting (continued)
    Faculty: Ron Kasznik

    Financial Statement Analysis

    In this session we examine the role of managerial judgment in making accounting decisions. We also discuss financial statement analysis and demonstrate how ratio analysis can provide valuable information for evaluating the business’ strategy, company’s health, and its overall operational performance.

    Pre-session preparation:

    • Videos: Understanding Financial Statements (there are 3 short videos; watch the first one before working on the Radiation Shields case.)
    • Case: Radiation Shields, Inc.

    Preparation Question(s):

    The spreadsheet attached at the end of the case is a useful format for recording the transactions and their effects on the company’s accounts. You should attempt to make as much progress as you can. When you are done, watch the next two videos (providing the case ‘solution’).

            12:40 PM - 2:00 PM | Lunch Break


            2:00 PM - 3:20 PM | Business Models
            Faculty: Haim Mendelson

            An Introduction

            In this session, we’ll introduce the concept of a business model and apply it to a few case examples, focusing on Airbnb. We’ll consider the process of business model development and analyze the evolution of the Airbnb business model in its first five years. We’ll then consider general characteristics of the Airbnb business model and how they carry over to other business models.

            Reading(s):

            • Reading: Business Models: A Quick Introduction
            • Video: The Airbnb Story
            • Case: Airbnb: The First Five Years

            Preparation Question(s):

            1. What types of value creation models can you find in the hotel industry? Where does Airbnb fit among these value creation models?
            2. Analyze the business model of Airbnb using the business model architecture framework in Business Models: A Quick Introduction (reading #1).
            3. What was Airbnb’s go-to-market strategy? What do you think about it?
            4. Did it make sense for Airbnb to pay for professional photography? Why or why not?
            5. Airbnb has to decide about a China strategy. What should Airbnb do about China?
            6. Did it make sense for Airbnb to go public in spite of the disastrous effect of COVID-19 on the travel industry?

            9:40 AM - 11:00 AM | Finance 1
            Faculty: Anne Beyer

            Financial Management

            All financing and investment decisions rely on the concepts of net present value and risk-adjusted returns but how these concepts are implemented varies depending on the situation. In our sessions, we ask the question “What is a good investment?” from the perspective of all stakeholders involved in the financing of ventures.

            We then take a close look at investments in new ventures. In the U.S. and across the world, most new businesses are bootstrapped, that is they are financed using only the founders’ personal funds and reinvesting cash received from early customers. Other ventures raise funds from investors. These investments can take many forms. In this session, we will discuss the most common forms of financing for new venture

            Reading(s):

            • Brealey/Myers/Allen: Principles of Corporate Finance
              • Chapter 2: How to Calculate Present Value?
              • Chapter 7: Introduction to Risk and Return
            • Real Options: Valuing Managerial Flexibility

            Preparation Question(s):

            • None

            5:00 PM - 7:20 PM | Elevator Pitches | E101, E102, E104 (GSB Map)

            Teams will have the opportunity to give brief venture idea pitches to industry experts for candid feedback. Your presentation should clearly define the problem you are trying to solve and the solution you are proposing. Each team will have two separate elevator pitch sessions. Further event guidelines can be found on the Elevator Pitch assignment page and the schedule can be found on the schedule page.

            Teams will present to 1-2 panelists in each session. The names of the panelists are not shared in advance, nor will your venture description be shared with panelists. It should not be assumed that pitch judges are experts in your field. Go to the Elevator Pitch assignment page for more details.

            11:00 AM - 11:20 AM | BREAK (faculty discretion; times are approximate)


            11:20 AM - 12:40 PM | Ignite Circles
            Facilitators: Ignite Staff

            Now that you have had your first check-ins with Yossi and Elevator pitches, you will have an opportunity to further refine your venture project idea through Ignite Circles. In this workshop, you will be placed in a small group with participants from different venture teams to share your venture project ideas and get peer feedback. Come prepared to explain your venture project idea, learn about the other venture projects in the program, and make some new connections with classmates outside of your project group.
